{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505230"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:27:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:27:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2422"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2422"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.05,0.19,0.05,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111129"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2422"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93253"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11224"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1823"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1881"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28472"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42489"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43148"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44637"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45171"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111129"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-hour history of cramping right-sided abdominal pain. The pain starts in his flank and radiates down into his scrotum. He has never had symptoms like this before. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft to palpation with right flank tenderness. Urinalysis shows haemoglobin +++. Intramuscular diclofenac is given.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT KUB is ordered (Image). A 6 mm stone is seen at the vesicoureteric junction on other images. The patient is kept under observation. During his assessment the medical staff are mindful that some form of surgical intervention might be required.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most strongly indicates the need for surgical intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abnormal vital signs","Microscopic haematuria with pyuria","Intractable pain despite analgesia","Renal angle tenderness","Solitary kidney"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic symptoms of renal colic, confirmed by CT imaging showing a 6 mm ureteric stone. When managing ureteric stones, most can be treated conservatively with analgesia and hydration, but certain factors necessitate urgent intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESolitary kidney\u003C/strong\u003E is the most critical indication for surgical intervention among the options provided. In a patient with a solitary kidney, any obstruction poses a significant risk to overall renal function as there is no contralateral kidney to compensate. This represents a urological emergency requiring prompt intervention to prevent permanent renal damage. In this case the right kidney is clearly present, but the left kidney is absent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbnormal vital signs\u003C/strong\u003E such as tachycardia and hypertension are common in renal colic due to pain and sympathetic activation. While concerning vital signs (particularly fever suggesting infection) may indicate a need for intervention, the modest changes seen in this patient are consistent with pain and do not necessarily mandate surgical management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMicroscopic haematuria with pyuria\u003C/strong\u003E is a common finding in renal colic. While pyuria may raise concern for infection, this finding alone without other signs of infection (fever, elevated white cell count) does not necessarily indicate a need for immediate surgical intervention. If there were signs of infection with obstruction (pyonephrosis), this would be an emergency requiring prompt decompression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntractable pain despite analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E is a relative indication for intervention, but many patients can be managed with escalating analgesia regimens including opioids if necessary. While persistent severe pain may eventually lead to intervention for symptomatic relief, it is not as urgent as protecting renal function in a solitary kidney.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal angle tenderness\u003C/strong\u003E is a common finding in renal colic and, like haematuria, is expected rather than an indication for surgical intervention. It reflects the inflammatory response to the stone but does not independently indicate obstruction severity or risk to renal function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important indications for urgent intervention in renal colic include signs of infection with obstruction (pyonephrosis), bilateral obstruction, and stones unlikely to pass spontaneously (generally \u0026gt;7 mm, though this patient\u0027s 6 mm stone has approximately 50% chance of spontaneous passage). The presence of a solitary kidney, however, represents the most critical indication among those listed as it carries the highest risk of permanent renal damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The presence of a solitary kidney is a clear indication for active intervention in the management of renal tract calculi.","Ureteric stones 6-7 mm in size have approximately 50% chance of spontaneous passage, but surgical intervention is indicated when there is risk to renal function.","Non-contrast CT of the kidneys, ureters, and bladder (CT KUB) is the gold standard investigation for suspected renal colic."],"references":["Sewell J, Katz DJ, Shoshany O, Love C. Urolithiasis \u2013 Ten things every general practitioner should know. Aust Fam Physician. 2017;46(9):648\u201352. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28892595/","Zumstein V, Betschart P, Abt D, Schmid HP, Panje CM, Putora PM. Surgical management of urolithiasis \u2013 a systematic analysis of available guidelines. BMC Urol. 2018;18(25). Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29636048/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93253"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2422"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18361"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18361"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9814902a-3628-4399-b827-48d25335fba0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9814902a-3628-4399-b827-48d25335fba0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":491,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93253"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-09T10:43:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-09T10:44:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2422"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111129"}}